---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout title="Diabetic Ketoacidosis" description="Simulation case for diabetic ketoacidosis management.">
  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/`}>Cases</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>Diabetic Ketoacidosis</span>
  </div>

  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">Endocrine</span>
    <h1>Diabetic Ketoacidosis</h1>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>⏱ Duration: 45 minutes</span>
      <span>📊 Difficulty: Intermediate</span>
      <span>👥 Team Size: 2–4</span>
      <span>🏥 Setting: Emergency Department</span>
    </div>
    <div class="tags" style="margin-top:1rem;">
      <span class="tag">Endocrine</span>
      <span class="tag">Fluids</span>
      <span class="tag">Insulin</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Case Overview</h2>
    <p>
      A 22-year-old male, Mr. Tyler Hughes, with known Type 1 Diabetes is brought to the
      Emergency Department by his roommate with a 2-day history of nausea, vomiting, polyuria,
      polydipsia, and progressive confusion. He ran out of insulin 3 days ago.
    </p>
    <p>
      Learners must diagnose DKA using clinical and laboratory criteria, initiate fluid
      resuscitation, correct electrolyte abnormalities, and safely introduce an insulin
      infusion while monitoring for complications including cerebral edema.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Patient Information</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Name:</strong> Tyler Hughes</li>
      <li><strong>Age:</strong> 22 years</li>
      <li><strong>Gender:</strong> Male</li>
      <li><strong>Weight:</strong> 75 kg</li>
      <li><strong>PMH:</strong> Type 1 Diabetes (diagnosed age 12)</li>
      <li><strong>Medications:</strong> Insulin glargine 24 units nightly, Insulin lispro sliding scale</li>
      <li><strong>Allergies:</strong> NKDA</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Initial Vital Signs &amp; Labs</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>BP:</strong> 100/62 mmHg</li>
      <li><strong>HR:</strong> 118 bpm</li>
      <li><strong>RR:</strong> 26 breaths/min (Kussmaul breathing)</li>
      <li><strong>SpO₂:</strong> 98% on room air</li>
      <li><strong>Glucose:</strong> 28.4 mmol/L (511 mg/dL)</li>
      <li><strong>pH:</strong> 7.18 | <strong>HCO₃:</strong> 8 mEq/L | <strong>Anion Gap:</strong> 24</li>
      <li><strong>K⁺:</strong> 5.8 mEq/L (depleted total body, elevated serum)</li>
      <li><strong>Urine ketones:</strong> 3+</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
    <ul class="objective-list">
      <li>Diagnose DKA using clinical criteria (hyperglycemia, ketoacidosis, anion gap)</li>
      <li>Identify and correct precipitating factor (insulin omission)</li>
      <li>Initiate appropriate IV fluid resuscitation (0.9% NaCl first bolus)</li>
      <li>Manage potassium replacement before starting insulin infusion (K &gt;3.5 mEq/L)</li>
      <li>Calculate and initiate continuous regular insulin infusion</li>
      <li>Monitor for and recognize signs of cerebral edema</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Scenario Progression</h2>
    <h4>Phase 1 – Diagnosis (0–10 min)</h4>
    <p>
      Assessment, ABG, BMP, urinalysis confirm severe DKA. Large bore IV access obtained;
      1L NS bolus initiated.
    </p>
    <h4>Phase 2 – Fluid &amp; Electrolyte Management (10–30 min)</h4>
    <p>
      Repeat labs show K⁺ improving. Potassium replacement added to fluids. Insulin
      infusion started at 0.1 units/kg/hr. Glucose checked hourly.
    </p>
    <h4>Phase 3 – Monitoring &amp; Complications (30–45 min)</h4>
    <p>
      Glucose drops rapidly; dextrose added to IV fluids. Patient develops headache and
      vomiting — cerebral edema suspected. Mannitol administered and neurology consulted.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Debriefing Guide</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Were all three DKA criteria correctly identified?</li>
      <li>Was potassium checked and supplemented before insulin administration?</li>
      <li>Was the glucose drop rate monitored to prevent overly rapid correction?</li>
      <li>Were the signs of cerebral edema recognized promptly?</li>
      <li>Was the transition to subcutaneous insulin planned appropriately?</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div style="margin-top: 2rem;">
    <a href={`${base}cases/`} class="btn btn-primary" style="background: var(--color-primary); color: #fff;">← Back to Cases</a>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
